---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Security — Tasca"
  description="How Tasca isolates untrusted input, sandboxes agent execution, and protects secrets at rest. Threat model, trust tiers, and responsible disclosure."
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Trust &amp; isolation</span>
      <h1>Security model</h1>
      <p class="lead">Coding agents run real commands on real machines. Tasca treats untrusted, externally-filed work as a first-class threat — and gates it before any of it can reach a shell.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRINCIPLE CARDS -->
  <section class="container" style="margin-top:48px;">
    <div class="grid grid-3">
      <div class="card card-hover">
        <div class="feature-ico"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 15a3 3 0 100-6 3 3 0 000 6z"/><path d="M19.4 15a1.6 1.6 0 00.3 1.8l.1.1a2 2 0 11-2.8 2.8l-.1-.1a1.6 1.6 0 00-2.7 1.1V21a2 2 0 11-4 0v-.1A1.6 1.6 0 005 19.4a2 2 0 11-2.8-2.8l.1-.1A1.6 1.6 0 003.4 14a2 2 0 010-4h.1A1.6 1.6 0 005 7.3a2 2 0 112.8-2.8l.1.1A1.6 1.6 0 0010 3.4V3a2 2 0 014 0v.1a1.6 1.6 0 002.7 1.1l.1-.1A2 2 0 1119.6 7l-.1.1a1.6 1.6 0 00.3 2.7"/></svg></div>
        <h3 class="h3">Untrusted input can't execute</h3>
        <p class="body">External clients propose and comment. They never trigger a run. An internal human must promote a ticket to agent-ready first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-hover">
        <div class="feature-ico"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="3"/><path d="M9 9h6v6H9z"/></svg></div>
        <h3 class="h3">Every external run is sandboxed</h3>
        <p class="body">Ephemeral container per run — no host filesystem, no secrets, restricted egress. Other clients' repos are never visible.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-hover">
        <div class="feature-ico"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="4" y="11" width="16" height="10" rx="2"/><path d="M8 11V7a4 4 0 018 0v4"/></svg></div>
        <h3 class="h3">Secrets encrypted at rest</h3>
        <p class="body">Passwords are argon2id. Provider tokens and org keys are AES-256-GCM under a dedicated server key — never the JWT secret.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- DETAIL -->
  <div class="container">
    <div class="legal-wrap">
      <aside class="legal-toc">
        <nav aria-label="On this page">
          <div class="th">On this page</div>
          <a href="#threat">Threat model</a>
          <a href="#trust">Trust tiers</a>
          <a href="#sandbox">Sandboxed execution</a>
          <a href="#injection">Prompt-injection containment</a>
          <a href="#secrets">Secrets &amp; auth</a>
          <a href="#roles">Roles &amp; access</a>
          <a href="#egress">Hosting &amp; isolation</a>
          <a href="#disclosure">Disclosure</a>
        </nav>
      </aside>

      <div class="prose">
        <section id="threat">
          <h2><span class="num">01</span> Threat model</h2>
          <p>Tasca dispatches coding agents that run shell commands, edit files, and open pull requests. Many agents default to permissive execution. That is acceptable for trusted, internal work — and dangerous the moment untrusted input enters the system.</p>
          <p>The primary risk is a ticket authored or influenced by an external party that causes an agent to execute attacker-controlled instructions on a host with access to source, secrets, or the network. Tasca's security model is built to make that path impossible by default.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="trust">
          <h2><span class="num">02</span> Trust tiers</h2>
          <p>Identity and roles live in the team layer, and that is where the gate is enforced — before any dispatch reaches a local executor. It cannot be bypassed at the execution seam.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>External / guest</strong> is propose-only. Guests file and comment. They cannot start a run.</li>
            <li><strong>Promotion is explicit.</strong> An internal member promotes a proposed ticket to agent-ready. Untrusted input never directly triggers execution.</li>
            <li><strong>Local-only mode</strong> (no team layer) is treated as fully trusted and internal — there is no external surface to gate.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="sandbox">
          <h2><span class="num">03</span> Sandboxed execution</h2>
          <p>Any external-touch execution runs inside an ephemeral container, provisioned with only the client's worktree and toolchain. The run has:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>No host filesystem</strong> and <strong>no host secrets</strong>.</li>
            <li><strong>Restricted egress</strong>, scoped to what the task legitimately needs.</li>
            <li><strong>No visibility</strong> into other clients' repositories.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The model host and GPU stay on the host machine; the sandbox reaches inference over the network. Permissive agent defaults are flipped to <span class="kbd">supervised</span> / approval-gated on any non-trusted path.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="injection">
          <h2><span class="num">04</span> Prompt-injection containment</h2>
          <p>Tasca can re-dispatch an agent with PR review comments injected as a follow-up prompt. Because review text is attacker-reachable on external work, that behavior is <strong>off by default</strong> for any ticket carrying external comments. Review feedback never silently becomes an instruction the agent obeys.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="secrets">
          <h2><span class="num">05</span> Secrets &amp; auth</h2>
          <p>Credentials are never stored in plaintext.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Passwords</strong> are hashed with argon2id.</li>
            <li><strong>Provider tokens and org API keys</strong> are encrypted with AES-256-GCM, keyed by a dedicated <span class="kbd">SERVER_ENCRYPTION_KEY</span> — decoupled from the JWT secret, so rotating JWTs can't orphan stored keys.</li>
            <li><strong>Sessions</strong> use short-lived access tokens with refresh-token rotation and reuse detection; a detected reuse revokes the whole session family.</li>
            <li><strong>Login, refresh, and OAuth callbacks</strong> are rate-limited, with account lockout after repeated failures.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The org Anthropic key powers the PM-assistant only — never worker agents — and is validated on entry, masked on read, and excluded from every log and audit payload.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="roles">
          <h2><span class="num">06</span> Roles &amp; access</h2>
          <p>Four roles, each a strict superset of the next. The guest tier is the security boundary for external collaboration.</p>
          <table class="roles-table">
            <thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Can do</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><span class="role-pill owner">owner</span></td><td>Billing, org keys, delete org, plus everything an admin can do.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><span class="role-pill">admin</span></td><td>Manage members, projects, agents, sprints; set the org key; promote proposals.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><span class="role-pill">member</span></td><td>Create and assign tickets, review PRs, run agents.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><span class="role-pill guest">guest</span></td><td>Propose-only: file and comment. Cannot trigger execution.</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </section>

        <section id="egress">
          <h2><span class="num">07</span> Hosting &amp; data isolation</h2>
          <p>On hosted Tasca, each organization's data is isolated per tenant and encrypted in transit and at rest. We do not use your code, tickets, or prompts to train models. The product bundles no third-party analytics or crash reporting — the only data we process is what the service needs to run, described in our <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>.</p>
          <p>You can export or delete your organization's data at any time. And because Tasca's core is open source under Apache-2.0, you can move to a self-hosted deployment whenever you want — the product is identical.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="disclosure">
          <h2><span class="num">08</span> Responsible disclosure</h2>
          <p>If you find a vulnerability, please report it privately before disclosing publicly. Email <a href="mailto:security@tasca.dev">security@tasca.dev</a> with steps to reproduce and the affected version. We aim to acknowledge within two business days and to coordinate a fix and disclosure timeline with you.</p>
          <p>Because Tasca is self-hosted, operators are responsible for patching their own deployments. Security-relevant releases are tagged and noted in the changelog.</p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>

<style is:global>
.roles-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 18px; font-size: 14px; }
.roles-table th { text-align: left; font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--fg-4); padding: 0 14px 10px 0; font-weight: 500; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); }
.roles-table td { padding: 14px 14px 14px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); color: var(--fg-3); vertical-align: top; line-height: 1.5; }
.roles-table td:first-child { white-space: nowrap; }
.role-pill { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 7px; font-family: var(--f-mono); font-size: 12px; padding: 4px 11px; border-radius: var(--r-tag); border: 1px solid var(--line-2); color: var(--fg-2); }
.role-pill.guest { color: var(--fg-3); }
.role-pill.owner { color: var(--amber); border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--amber) 40%, transparent); }
</style>
